When you call `condition.wait();`, you are calling: [Objects.wait()][1], and this call requires :

&gt; The current thread must own this object&#39;s monitor.

so you would have to add:

    synchronized (condition) {
       // ...
       condition.wait()
    }

and this would be required in both your classes, and would not actually make your class work as expected.

But, what you actually want is to call [Condition.await()][2]. It does not require `synchronized` as `Objects.wait`.

The problem with your code should still persist in that there is no clear way on how to hand the processing between threads. Usually Condition.await() is called when the thread recognizes that there is no work for it. Below code is  my try at fixing it:

    static class PrintUseReentranLock2 implements Runnable{
        ReentrantLock lock;
        Condition condition;
        int n; //f ds
        int i;

        public PrintUseReentranLock2(int n){
            this.n = n;
            this.i = 0;
            this.lock = new ReentrantLock();
            this.condition = lock.newCondition();
        }

        @Override
        public void run(){
            while(i&lt;n){
                lock.lock();
                try {
                    while (Integer.valueOf(Thread.currentThread().getName()) != i%2)
                        condition.await();
                    if(i%2==0) System.out.println(&quot;A&quot;);
                    else System.out.println(&quot;B&quot;);
                    i++;
                    condition.signal();
                } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                    throw new RuntimeException(e);
                } finally {
                    lock.unlock();
                }
            }
        }
    }
    public static void test2(){
        PrintUseReentranLock2 p = new PrintUseReentranLock2(10);
        Thread t1 = new Thread(p, &quot;0&quot;);
        Thread t2 = new Thread(p, &quot;1&quot;);
        t1.start();
        t2.start();
    }

Now, both threads take turns at processing `i` variable.


